law.text:
A married woman may do any of the following, as if she were unmarried:
engage in a business;
make a contract with any person, including her husband, whether or not she is engaged in business;
bind herself and her assigns by a covenant running with or related to real property or chattels real deeded to her on or after March 19, 1867;
form a partnership with any person, including her husband;
sue on any contract, including a contract made with her husband;
sue for the recovery, security, or protection of her property;
sue for any tort committed against her; and
appoint counsel to represent her in an action brought under § 4-205(b) or (c) or § 4-301(b) of this title.
